{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f84d29d-8579-42a2-addb-da7aa29cabdd","content":"Here's what's likely wrong in each case:\n\n**1. `GoToAsync(\"productdetails\")` throws an exception**\n\nThe route isn't registered. Pages not defined in the Shell visual hierarchy (XAML) must be explicitly registered:\n\n```csharp\n// In AppShell constructor or MauiProgram.cs\nRouting.RegisterRoute(\"productdetails\", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));\n```\n\nThen navigate with: `await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(\"productdetails\");`\n\n---\n\n**2. `GoToAsync(\"//products/active\")` navigates but nothing visible changes**\n\nMost likely you're already on that route — absolute navigation to the current location is a no-op. Verify with `Shell.Current.CurrentState.Location`. Another common cause: the `ShellContent` with `Route=\"active\"` is the only content in its `Tab`, so there's no visible top-tab bar to indicate a switch.\n\n**Fix:** Check the current route before navigating, or restructure so sibling `ShellContent` items exist to produce a visible tab bar.\n\n---\n\n**3. App takes 3 seconds to start with 12 pages**\n\nYou're likely instantiating pages directly in XAML instead of deferring creation. Shell eagerly constructs all pages defined inline.\n\n**Fix:** Use `ContentTemplate` with `DataTemplate` for lazy loading:\n\n```xml\n<!-- Slow: page created at startup -->\n<ShellContent Route=\"active\">\n    <local:ActivePage />\n</ShellContent>\n\n<!-- Fast: page created only when navigated to -->\n<ShellContent Route=\"active\"\n              ContentTemplate=\"{DataTemplate local:ActivePage}\" />\n```\n\nThis defers construction of all 12 pages until the user actually navigates to them.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5a91372d-90cb-4383-bdec-8adb1f88c672","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about three common .NET MAUI Shell navigation issues. These are well-known patterns I can answer from knowledge without needing to search a codebase. Let me provide concise, accurate answers.\n\n1. `GoToAsync(\"productdetails\")` throws an exception - This is likely because the route isn't registered. In Shell, routes that aren't defined in the visual hierarchy (XAML) must be registered with `Routing.RegisterRoute`.\n\n2. `GoToAsync(\"//products/active\")` navigates but nothing visible changes - This is likely because the route resolves to a tab/page that's already the current one, or more commonly, the ShellContent doesn't have its `ContentTemplate` set properly, or the page is cached and not refreshing. Actually, the most common cause is that the Shell visual hierarchy has the route defined but the `ContentTemplate` or `Content` isn't properly set, OR the Shell items aren't visible (IsVisible=false or have no content). Another common issue: if \"active\" is a ShellContent under a Tab called \"products\", navig\n\nThe most common reason nothing visually changes with absolute route navigation is that the items are defined but the Tab or FlyoutItem doesn't visibly switch because the Shell structure is wrong—like multiple ShellContents under the same Tab without proper top tabs rendering—or the current route is already \"//products/active\" so nothing actually changes. navigating to it again doesn't trigger a visual change\n\nThe issue is likely that the `ShellContent` either lacks a `ContentTemplate` or `Content` property, so there's nothing to display, or you're already viewing that route and the navigation doesn't produce a visible state change. Another possibility is that a parent item has `IsVisible=\"False\"`, preventing the content from showing even though the route resolves successfully. I'm circling back on this—the most likely culprit is that the content at `//products/active` exists in the hierarchy so navigation succeeds, but the actual page or component rendered there is either empty or misconfigured, which is why nothing appears to change visually. The core issues boil down to three things: either the route isn't registered in the routing table, or you're already at that location so navigation has no effect, or the `ShellContent` is instantiating pages eagerly instead of using a `DataTemplate` for lazy loading. The practical fix is to ensure routes are registered, verify you're not already on the target route, and use `ContentTemplate` with `DataTemplate` to defer page creation until needed.","outputTokens":1994,"requestId":"A42D:3F23E5:51DFB7:5F5C27:69F00848"},"id":"48a71ad1-66ea-4dd3-a16d-f8c6652db042","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:08:04.099Z","parentId":"038dd50b-ebbf-4ff1-9ad4-1fbc700a01cb"}
